<subSubSection lastPageId="14" lastPageNumber="23" pageId="13" pageNumber="22" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph blockId="13.[563,1023,439,466]" box="[563,1023,439,466]" pageId="13" pageNumber="22">
<heading box="[563,1023,439,466]" centered="true" fontSize="11" level="2" pageId="13" pageNumber="22" reason="2">
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="THOMSON" baseAuthorityYear="1869" box="[563,855,440,466]" class="Insecta" family="Sphaeroceridae" genus="Poecilosomella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="angulata">
<emphasis box="[563,855,440,466]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="22">Poecilosomella angulata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species group
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="13.[317,1270,510,715]" lastBlockId="14.[317,1270,439,853]" lastPageId="14" lastPageNumber="23" pageId="13" pageNumber="22">
The characteristics of this species group are as follows. Frons (postfrons) microtomentose (i.e. not shiny), 2 (1) pairs of fronto-orbitals. Mesonotum microtomentose, mostly dark, with silvery pattern. Genal seta comparatively short and fine, or not separable in the row of genal setae. Wing not much patterned: diffuse brown spots are around base of R 
<subScript attach="left" box="[711,741,664,680]" fontSize="7" pageId="13" pageNumber="22">2+3</subScript>
, of R 
<subScript attach="left" box="[807,836,664,680]" fontSize="7" pageId="13" pageNumber="22">4+5</subScript>
and on apices of radial veins. Costal vein terminates at vein R 
<subScript attach="left" box="[605,634,699,715]" fontSize="7" pageId="13" pageNumber="22">4+5</subScript>
, or produced slightly behind it. False vein from cubital vein does not close a cubital cell. At least hind tibia bicolourous, there are pale rings on the dark tibiae. In the 
<collectingRegion box="[667,844,475,501]" country="Republic of the Congo" name="Orientale" pageId="14" pageNumber="23">Oriental region</collectingRegion>
there are a number of species, which fit to this diagnosis, but only three (plus one) species in the Afrotropical region, incl. a new species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
